Kiess reads the five-city realm through the Evermeet lesson: secrecy accumulates contradictions until catastrophic collapse.
Anti-secrecy charter and three-power governance are structural responses to Evermeet's identified cause of death.
Realm stability requires institutional information sharing; sealed warrants and classified registries are realm-level risks.
Roc Road position makes Kiess the continent's northern logistics anchor; route security and caravan law are primary concerns.
City relations governed by disclosure: Midgaard's sealed archives cause friction; Kowloon's Black Ledger is philosophically incompatible; Kiess most agrees with Rakuen.
Three tracked events: Evermeet collapse (secrecy failure), Plague Mandate (emergency powers without sunset).
Also tracked: the Oath-Crossing, when Midgaard and Kowloon committed to coexistence over dominance competition.
Anti-sealed-warrant doctrine is a structural commitment equivalent to Kowloon's wall protocol — not a negotiable policy.

flags RAKUEN
---
Rakuen views the five-city realm as a burden-distribution problem: unclaimed necessary work always reaches Rakuen.
The city absorbs disaster recovery costs, emergency housing, and infrastructure other cities use but do not fund.
Three annexation petitions to Midgaard sought resource recognition, not dependency. All three refused.
Rakuen continues absorbing the same costs regardless of annexation outcome.
Realm stability rests on recovery capacity; no disaster-recovery node means the first major crisis cascades.
Garden Ledger records seven multi-city crises where Rakuen intervention prevented regional route failure.
Rakuen appears in five-city records as annexation refusals and emergency requests — neither captures its role.
City relations: cooperative with Kiess on burden principles; strained with Midgaard on resource recognition; aligned with Mafdet on route-resilience.
Garden Ledger: five cities depend on each other, acknowledge it when forced to, and compete for shared credit.

